{{technique}}

'''Parboiling''' is the act of partly cooking an ingredient by boiling for less than the full time needed to cook it. For example, [[Cookbook:Potato|potatoes]] and other vegetables may be parboiled before being roasted (as in [[Cookbook:Roast Potatoes|roast potatoes]]), or green beans may be parboiled (and immediately chilled in cold water) as a preparation for freezing.

This technique is also used as a method to quickly cook [[Cookbook:Pork|pork]] ribs before grilling, although I would never, ever, in my life, do this. You get pork broth if you boil ribs!

